+  "response": "I have diagnosed and resolved all the issues across the different services and the `EventBus` that were causing the tests to fail.\n\nHere is a summary of the fixes applied:\n\n1. **`src/billing/calculator.ts`**:\n   - Fixed premature intermediate rounding when calculating discounts and tax. We now maintain floating-point precision throughout the calculation and only apply rounding to 2 decimal places before returning the final breakdown, solving the rounding error during multi-item calculations.\n\n2. **`src/billing/service.ts`**:\n   - The `handleRefund` event listener was originally passed to the event bus without being bound to the service instance. Added `.bind(this)` to correctly preserve the `this` context so that `this.payments` is no longer `undefined`.\n\n3. **`src/orders/repository.ts`**:\n   - Fixed data loss during updates. The `update()` method was completely overwriting order objects with just the fields passed in the `updates` object. Changed it to merge the existing data via `{ ...existing, ...updates }`, ensuring details like `items` or `customerId` aren't wiped out when updating the order status.\n\n4. **`src/orders/service.ts`**:\n   - Fixed an off-by-one window check where the service rejected a refund strictly if the time was `>= 30` days. Changed to strictly `> 30` days to allow refunds exactly on day 30, as required by business logic.\n\n5. **`src/inventory/service.ts`**:\n   - In `handleOrderCancelled`, removed an early return that looked for `eventWithItems.status === 'cancelled'`. Since `OrderCancelledEvent` does not hold a `status` field, this condition was consistently evaluating to `undefined !== 'cancelled'` and preventing cancelled orders from releasing their stock reservation.\n\n6. **`src/events/bus.ts`**:\n   - Refactored `EventBus` to use an instance-level handlers map instead of a module-level global cache. The tests were instantiating a new `EventBus` for every `beforeEach()` execution but bleeding state by constantly adding more copies of the same callback to the global handlers map. This caused duplicate event handling logic across tests resulting in false `Insufficient stock` assertions during concurrent or canceled operations.\n\nThe `npm run build` and `npm run lint` commands have both executed successfully, confirming the system's structural integrity, and `npm test` now shows all 34 tests passing cleanly.",
